This ad might be the best assessment ever produced about America’s twisted, toxic, diseased relationship with guns and what it’s done to us. Thanks for posting this, @katiecouric. And follow @shannonrwatts. She’s doing the good work.

#Repost @katiecouric
・・・
The United States has averaged nearly two mass shootings a day this year, according to the Gun Violence Archive, and has had more than 600 mass shootings every year since 2020. As my friend @shannonrwatts so aptly put it, “we aren’t numb — we’re traumatized.” 

Assault weapons and high capacity magazines are often used in mass shootings, but research shows a prohibition on assault weapons can prevent mass shooting fatalities and active shooter events  According to a study from everytown, researchers estimate that if we still had a federal Assault Weapon Ban, we’d see 70% fewer mass shooting deaths.

In July 2022, the House passed the Assault Weapons Ban — the first time in almost 20 years that lawmakers have passed a measure to reinstate the expired federal ban. Since then, it has been sitting with the Senate and will expire on December 31st if senators don’t act now. Make your voices heard and urge your representatives to pass the Assault Weapons Ban.  Go to the link in my bio to finds scripts and contact information for your senators.

Christmas in NYC.

📷 Mary Ellen Mark

#Repost @nyhistory
・・・
Though legend has it that Santa Claus hails from the North Pole—he was actually a New Yorker who came into the world on West 23rd Street in what is now Chelsea. ⁣
⁣
The modern Santa was born in the imagination of Clement Clarke Moore, a scholar who penned a whimsical poem about St. Nicholas, the patron of old Dutch New York, for the amusement of his six children at Christmastime. Soon after the publication of "A Visit from St. Nicholas," St. Nicholas became a popular feature of American Christmas celebrations. Moore's poem permanently connected St. Nicholas to Christmas, and led to our idea of Santa Claus. ⁣

Santa's popularity, appearance and many of the holiday traditions that surround him owe much to the imaginative work of two other New Yorkers: Washington Irving, the creator of Knickerbocker's History of New York, and Thomas Nast, an artist whose drawings of Santa were reproduced all over the country in the years following the Civil War.
